--><ns4147:section xmlns:ns4147="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.processControl.runningProcessForegroundBackground">

  <ns4148:title xmlns:ns4148="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Launching applications in the fore- and background</ns4148:title>

  <ns4149:para xmlns:ns4149="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    An interactive process is typically started by simply entering the command. For example
    <ns4150:cmdsynopsis xmlns:ns4150="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns4151:command xmlns:ns4151="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
find /home/penguin/work  *.java   
   </ns4151:command></ns4150:cmdsynopsis>        
  </ns4149:para>  
  <ns4152:para xmlns:ns4152="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    To start a process in the background, you simply add an ampersand (&amp;) after the command.
    For example, to print a text document within a background process we can issue the command
    <ns4153:cmdsynopsis xmlns:ns4153="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns4154:command xmlns:ns4154="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
lp myFile.txt &amp;      
    </ns4154:command></ns4153:cmdsynopsis>
  </ns4152:para>
  
  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" href="jobs.docbook"/>
</ns4147:section>